                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/2573a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador to the Greek Government in Exile</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">at Cairo</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-03T12:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 3, 1944—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>65 Greek. Though knowing of Greek concern as to Russian attitude regarding
                    Bulgarian occupation of Thrace and of Macedonia, the British Foreign Office as
                    yet has had no suggestion that the matter may be raised by Greece. The British
                    Ambassador in Moscow has been advised to state as soon as practicable the
                    British position that the pre-war frontiers of both Greece and Yugoslavia must
                    be restored and that the territory of neither country is subject to
                    dismemberment in order to influence the Bulgars.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
